In a statement following the mass shooting in Boulder, Colorado, President Biden expressed his condolences to the victims' families and emphasized the need for action to address gun violence. He acknowledged that there is still much unknown about the shooter's motivation and other details of the incident. The President praised the heroic efforts of the police and first responders, particularly Officer Eric Talley, who lost his life in the line of duty. President Biden called for commonsense measures to prevent future mass shootings, including a ban on assault weapons and high-capacity magazines, as well as closing loopholes in the background check system. He urged Congress to pass the two House-approved bills that address these issues. The President promised to provide more information as it becomes available and concluded by expressing his support for the families affected by gun violence in Colorado, Georgia, and throughout the country.